## Why it's split this way

**The core is BUSL** because it's what a funded competitor would clone wholesale to launch a
rival network. A licence-violating fork is unfundable and unauditable — no serious investor or
audit firm touches one. It's a **deterrent, not a wall**: it does not stop an anonymous
deployer, and it isn't meant to.

**The surface is MIT on purpose.** BUSL restricts *production use* — and running an organ
service (an indexer, a tier service, an FMEA watchdog, a Bob-card integrator) **is** production
use. Putting BUSL on the interfaces would tax the exact permissionless market this network
exists to create. The product is an accumulating canonical toolkit; a toolkit nobody may run is
not a toolkit.

So: **verify us, integrate with us, build on us — freely. Just don't fork the settlement core
and run it as a competing network without talking to us.**

